
MicroBooNE NuMI Lambda final-state study context
================================================

Purpose
-------

This file records the current analysis plan for a generator-level and
detector-facing study of Lambda final states in MicroBooNE under the NuMI
off-axis flux.  It is intended to live in the repository as plain-text
context for humans and LLMs.

The study is explicitly NOT framed as a DUNE overlap note.  The primary
goal is to understand production coverage, final-state composition, and
truth-level detector coverage for Lambda-bearing events in MicroBooNE.
A secondary, optional goal is a geometry-only comparison with SBND using
the same truth definitions.

Core analysis stance
--------------------

There are two coupled but distinct objects:

  (1) Physics / mechanism study:
      What produces a final-state Lambda on argon, and how much of the
      observed Lambda population comes from direct Lambda production,
      Sigma0 -> Lambda gamma feed-through, charged-Sigma exchange, or
      other strange channels?

  (2) Detector-facing measurement:
      What MicroBooNE can actually measure is a fiducial detached-Lambda
      topology, namely a neutrino interaction in the fiducial volume with
      a visible Lambda -> p pi- decay topology in the active detector,
      optionally with a CC muon tag.

The measurement should be defined by (2).  The decomposition into direct
Lambda, Sigma feed-through, associated kaon production, and higher-mass
hyperon channels is a model-dependent interpretation layered on top of
that measurement.

This is the key design choice.  Do not make the detector-facing signal
equal to "direct anti-nu_mu N -> mu+ Lambda".  That is a theory channel,
not a robust detector observable.

Scope
-----

Main scope:

  * final-state Lambda production in MicroBooNE under the NuMI beam;
  * generator-level production coverage;
  * hyperon ancestry and migration through FSI;
  * truth-level detector observability of Lambda -> p pi- topologies;
  * inclusive detector-facing Lambda topology categories.

Optional scope:

  * SBND comparison using the same post-FSI truth sample and the same
    truth-visible topology rules, with only the detector geometry changed;
  * GiBUU or NEUT cross-checks beyond the main NuWro/GENIE pair;
  * later full-reconstruction studies after the truth-level design is
    frozen.

Non-goals for the first pass:

  * no DUNE overlap study in the main analysis;
  * no attempt to publish a generator-independent extraction of direct
    Lambda or Sigma cross sections from the topology measurement alone;
  * no reliance on reconstruction-specific fake-topology estimates in the
    generator-only stage.

Canonical observable definitions
--------------------------------

Use four truth stages.  They must stay distinct in the ntuples and in the
plots.

  Stage A: primary strange production
      The strange baryon species at the neutrino interaction vertex,
      before intranuclear transport and before prompt decays.

  Stage B: strange baryon at nuclear exit
      The strange baryon species after FSI and after intranuclear
      transport, but before detector-medium propagation.

  Stage C: post-decay state in detector medium
      The Lambda decay position and daughters after propagation in liquid
      argon, before any reconstruction selection.

  Stage D: truth-visible topology
      A truth-level tag for whether the event contains a visible detached
      Lambda -> p pi- topology in the MicroBooNE active volume.

Important consequence:

  Sigma0 feed-through is a Stage A composition issue.
  Charged-Sigma exchange is a Stage A -> Stage B migration issue.
  Lambda acceptance is a Stage B/C -> Stage D issue.

Headline detector-facing signal
-------------------------------

Define the headline signal as:

  "inclusive fiducial Lambda topology"

meaning:

  * neutrino interaction vertex in the fiducial volume;
  * at least one true Lambda is present after transport;
  * a Lambda decays as Lambda -> p pi- in or near the active volume;
  * the daughter proton and pion satisfy truth-visible conditions.

This signal is inclusive in origin.  It includes:

  * direct Lambda production;
  * Sigma0 -> Lambda gamma feed-through;
  * Sigma+/-/0 -> Lambda through FSI or exchange;
  * associated K Y production if it ends in a visible Lambda topology;
  * higher-mass hyperon or Y pi contributions if they yield a visible
    Lambda.

This signal does NOT include:

  * events with no true Lambda that only fake a detached p pi- topology;
  * reconstruction-specific failures or false positives unless a later
    full detector/reco study is added.

Subchannels to define from the same truth sample
------------------------------------------------

The same inclusive truth sample should support multiple detector-facing
categories.  At minimum define:

  S0: inclusive Lambda topology
      No requirement on visible muon, kaon, gamma, or extra activity.

  S1: CC-tagged Lambda topology
      Same as S0, plus a visible muon candidate at truth level.

  S2: Lambda topology + visible kaon
      Same as S0, plus a visible final-state kaon tag.  This is the most
      direct detector handle on associated K Y production.

  S3: Lambda topology + low extra activity
      Same as S0, but with little additional visible hadronic activity.
      This is a QE-like control region, not the main inclusive signal.

  S4: Lambda topology + visible EM companion
      Same as S0, plus visible gamma or EM activity compatible with
      Sigma0 feed-through.  This is useful as an interpretation category,
      but should not be required by the headline signal.

  S5: Lambda topology with no visible muon
      NC-enriched or low-muon-visibility category.

Do NOT define "no showers" or "low extra activity" as part of the main
inclusive Lambda-topology signal.  Those requirements are useful for a
QE-like subsample, but they bias against visible Sigma0 gamma activity and
against associated production.

Physics decomposition to preserve in all samples
------------------------------------------------

Every event that reaches Stage D should carry an origin label.  Use a
small, explicit ancestry vocabulary rather than generator-specific process
IDs.  Recommended origin classes:

  O0  direct_Lambda
      Primary Lambda at the interaction vertex.

  O1  Sigma0_feedthrough
      Primary Sigma0 that becomes Lambda via Sigma0 -> Lambda gamma.

  O2  charged_Sigma_exchange
      Primary Sigma+ or Sigma- whose transport and/or exchange ends in a
      final-state Lambda.

  O3  neutral_Sigma_exchange
      Primary Sigma0 or Sigma-like state whose transport contributes to a
      final-state Lambda outside the simple prompt-decay feed-through.

  O4  associated_KY
      Primary associated kaon + hyperon production with final Lambda
      topology.

  O5  inelastic_hyperon_or_Ypi
      Higher-mass hyperon, Y pi, or inelastic strange channels that end in
      a visible Lambda topology.

  O6  other_strange
      Any other strange ancestry that yields a final visible Lambda.

  O7  no_true_Lambda
      Background class used only after reconstruction studies are added.

In practice, O1, O2, O4, and O5 are the load-bearing categories.

Core equations
--------------

For any phase-space point x, define:

  S_FSI(x)   = N_exit(x) / N_primary(x)
  A_topo(x)  = N_visible(x) / N_exit_or_postdecay(x)

where:

  N_primary      = Stage A yield,
  N_exit         = Stage B yield,
  N_visible      = Stage D yield.

For the inclusive detector-facing signal:

  N_visible_Lambda_topology
    = sum over origins o of
      N_primary(o) *
      P(Lambda at exit | o) *
      P(visible Lambda -> p pi- topology | exit, geometry) *
      A_topo

This factorization is conceptual.  The analysis should estimate the
factors from event records, not impose a hard analytic model.

Samples required
----------------

The sample plan has three layers:

  Layer 0: flux assets
  Layer 1: mechanism-control generator samples
  Layer 2: inclusive topology generator samples

Layer 0: flux assets
--------------------

Freeze the MicroBooNE NuMI flux inputs first.  Use:

  * updated MicroBooNE NuMI FHC flux histogram;
  * updated MicroBooNE NuMI RHC flux histogram;
  * direct FHC/RHC NuMI beam generation configurations.

Reason: rare strange channels are too expensive to generate directly with
overly narrow exact-count rejection loops if the only goal is phase-space
coverage and topology fractions.  Generate with the beam spectra used for the
analysis, keep the selected count floating, and carry the statistical
uncertainty.

Layer 1: mechanism-control samples
----------------------------------

These samples isolate direct Lambda, Sigma0 feed-through, and charged-
Sigma exchange.  They are the interpretation backbone, not the headline
measurement sample.

Mandatory NuWro controls:

  NW-DIR-numubar-p-na-flatE
      anti-nu_mu on free proton, flat E.
      Purpose: direct Lambda and Sigma0 production on proton.

  NW-DIR-numubar-n-na-flatE
      anti-nu_mu on free neutron, flat E.
      Purpose: Sigma- production on neutron.

  NW-DIR-numubar-Ar-off-flatE
      anti-nu_mu on argon, FSI off, flat E.
      Purpose: isolate nuclear initial-state effects without hyperon FSI.

  NW-DIR-numubar-Ar-on-flatE
      anti-nu_mu on argon, FSI on, flat E.
      Purpose: nominal direct-hyperon + transport sample.

Recommended NuWro variations:

  NW-DIR-numubar-Ar-on-flatE-potOff
      Hyperon potential off.

  NW-DIR-numubar-Ar-on-flatE-MAlo
      Lower axial-mass or relevant form-factor variant.

  NW-DIR-numubar-Ar-on-flatE-MAhi
      Higher axial-mass or relevant form-factor variant.

Optional if statistics permit:

  NW-DIR-numu-Ar-on-flatE
      nu_mu on argon, FSI on, flat E.
      Purpose: cross-check channels that populate Lambda through neutrino-
      induced associated production in the same framework.

Matching GENIE controls:

  GN-DIR-numubar-p-na-flatE
  GN-DIR-numubar-n-na-flatE
  GN-DIR-numubar-Ar-na-flatE

GENIE is not the nominal transport model for Sigma -> Lambda migration,
but it is the main production baseline and a necessary comparison point.

Optional GiBUU control:

  GB-DIR-numubar-Ar-na-flatE
      A transport-theory cross-check if available.

Layer 2: inclusive topology samples
-----------------------------------

These are the main measurement samples.  Generate all processes on argon,
then classify offline by ancestry and visible topology.

Mandatory inclusive samples:

  NW-INCL-numu-Ar-on-flatE
  NW-INCL-numubar-Ar-on-flatE
  GN-INCL-numu-Ar-na-flatE
  GN-INCL-numubar-Ar-na-flatE

Optional low-priority samples:

  NW-INCL-nue-Ar-on-flatE
  NW-INCL-nuebar-Ar-on-flatE
  GN-INCL-nue-Ar-na-flatE
  GN-INCL-nuebar-Ar-na-flatE

Rationale:

  * numu and numubar are mandatory because the detector-facing Lambda
    topology is not restricted to the direct anti-nu hyperon sector;
  * numu flux contributes through associated kaon + hyperon production and
    other final-state Lambda channels;
  * electron-flavor samples are likely subleading in NuMI but can be added
    later for completeness if needed.

Beam-weighted derived views
---------------------------

Do not generate separate beam-thrown files at first.  Instead derive:

  * FHC-weighted predictions from flat-E inclusive and control samples;
  * RHC-weighted predictions from flat-E inclusive and control samples.

This gives one common truth library with two beam projections.

Optional SBND geometry comparison
---------------------------------

If an SBND comparison is added, do not generate a separate physics sample.
Reuse the same post-FSI, post-decay truth records and apply the same
truth-visible topology rules in an SBND geometry pass.  Otherwise beam
differences and generator composition get mixed with the geometry effect.

Generator strategy
------------------

Nominal generator pair:

  * NuWro: nominal model for hyperon ancestry and Sigma -> Lambda
    migration;
  * GENIE: main production baseline and comparison point.

Why this pair:

  * NuWro is the one to trust first for hyperon transport studies,
    especially charged-Sigma exchange and Lambda enhancement from FSI;
  * GENIE remains essential for a production-level baseline and for
    understanding how sensitive the decomposition is to generator choice.

Optional cross-check generators:

  * GiBUU: transport-theory cross-check;
  * NEUT: later appendix after local verification of the relevant hyperon
    implementation.

Repository and build strategy
-----------------------------

A repository such as BuildEventGenerators is a good bootstrap, but it must
be modified for this analysis.  The minimum required changes are:

  * pin every generator version explicitly;
  * replace older MicroBooNE flux files with the updated NuMI flux assets;
  * add jobcards for free p, free n, argon FSI off, and argon FSI on;
  * preserve Sigma0 ancestry before automatic decays;
  * export a common reduced ntuple with ancestry fields;
  * support flat-E generation plus later FHC/RHC weighting.

Do not rely on "latest master" for NuWro or any other generator.  Use a
known tag or commit hash and record it in the repo.

Recommended sample naming convention
------------------------------------

Use a machine-readable sample name with fixed fields:

  [GEN]-[FAM]-[FLAVOR]-[TARGET]-[FSI]-[SPEC]-[VARIANT]

where:

  GEN      = NW, GN, GB, NT
  FAM      = DIR, INCL, TOPO, GEOM
  FLAVOR   = numu, numubar, nue, nuebar
  TARGET   = p, n, Ar
  FSI      = na, off, on
  SPEC     = flatE, FHCw, RHCw
  VARIANT  = nom, potOff, MAlo, MAhi, loose, nominal, tight, etc.

Examples:

  NW-DIR-numubar-Ar-on-flatE-nom
  GN-INCL-numu-Ar-na-flatE-nom
  NW-TOPO-numubar-Ar-on-FHCw-nominal
  NW-GEOM-numubar-Ar-on-FHCw-SBND-nominal

Truth record / reduced ntuple contract
--------------------------------------

The reduced ntuple is more important than the raw generator trees.  Every
analysis stage should write the same core fields.

Event identity and weights:

  * run, subrun, event;
  * generator name and version;
  * flux mode weight: flatE, FHC weight, RHC weight;
  * incoming neutrino PDG and energy.

Interaction-level kinematics:

  * E_nu;
  * Q2;
  * W;
  * x_Bj, y if available;
  * target nucleon / nucleus code;
  * interaction category label if available.

Primary strange ancestry:

  * primary strange baryon species before prompt decay;
  * primary kaon content;
  * primary associated-hyperon flags;
  * origin class O0..O7.

Nuclear-exit state:

  * strange baryon species at nuclear exit;
  * kaon species at nuclear exit;
  * extra nucleon multiplicities and kinetic energies;
  * extra pion multiplicities.

Detector-medium / post-decay state:

  * Lambda four-vector at exit or before decay;
  * Lambda decay vertex (x, y, z);
  * Lambda decay length and proper lifetime proxy if available;
  * daughter proton four-vector;
  * daughter pion four-vector;
  * daughter opening angle;
  * pointing angle of the Lambda candidate back to the neutrino vertex;
  * Sigma0 gamma four-vector if the parent was Sigma0;
  * visible kaon companion four-vectors;
  * visible EM companion flags;
  * extra visible energy estimate.

Truth-visible tags:

  * fiducial_vertex_flag;
  * lambda_decays_in_active_flag;
  * proton_visible_flag;
  * pion_visible_flag;
  * detached_vertex_flag;
  * visible_muon_flag;
  * visible_kaon_flag;
  * visible_gamma_flag;
  * low_extra_activity_flag;
  * topology_loose_flag;
  * topology_nominal_flag;
  * topology_tight_flag.

Ancestry-preservation rules
---------------------------

These rules are mandatory.  If they are violated, the analysis becomes
ambiguous.

  * Preserve the primary Sigma0 label before automatic Sigma0 -> Lambda
    gamma decay.  Otherwise Sigma0 feed-through is lost.
  * Preserve the primary Sigma+/- label before transport.  Otherwise
    charged-Sigma exchange cannot be measured.
  * Keep both primary and nuclear-exit strange-baryon species.
  * Record kaon companions at both the primary vertex and detector-visible
    stage.
  * Do not trust generator process IDs alone to define origin classes.
    Construct origin classes explicitly from ancestry.

Truth-visible working points
----------------------------

Use three truth-visible working points derived from the same Stage C
record.  This is better than one hard cut, because generator-level studies
must acknowledge uncertainty in the final reconstruction thresholds.

Loose working point:

  * fiducial vertex;
  * Lambda decays inside or very near active volume;
  * daughter proton and pion are both nontrivial in visible range;
  * minimal detached-vertex requirement.

Nominal working point:

  * fiducial vertex;
  * Lambda decays inside active volume;
  * daughter proton and pion each satisfy nominal visibility thresholds;
  * detached vertex exceeds a nominal separation threshold;
  * daughters have enough opening angle to support a V0-like topology.

Tight working point:

  * all nominal requirements;
  * stronger daughter visibility thresholds;
  * stronger displaced-vertex and opening-angle requirements;
  * optionally stronger containment conditions.

Practical rule:

  start from daughter momentum or range thresholds that are consistent with
  the published MicroBooNE Lambda restricted phase space, then map them to
  truth-visible track-length proxies if needed.

Axes and coverage variables
---------------------------

Do not center the note on (E_nu, Q2) alone.  Keep it as a secondary plane.
For Lambda final states, the natural axes are hadron-centric.

Production / mechanism planes:

  * (E_nu, W)
  * (Q2, W)
  * (E_nu, primary strange species fraction)

Final-state Lambda planes:

  * (p_Lambda, cos(theta_Lambda))
  * (T_Lambda or p_Lambda, decay length)
  * (decay length, daughter opening angle)

Topology / detector planes:

  * (z_decay, r_decay) or x-z and y-z decay maps
  * (p_p, p_pi) for daughter visibility
  * (p_K, extra visible energy) for associated-production context
  * (E_gamma, z_decay) or a simple gamma-visibility flag for Sigma0

Each phase-space plane should support the same stage sequence:
primary -> exit -> post-decay -> truth-visible.

Plot plan and visual grammar
----------------------------

Baseline grammar to keep:

  * normalized one-dimensional spectra;
  * 70/90/99 percent coverage contours in key two-dimensional planes.

Expanded grammar for this analysis:

  A. Stage-contour overlays
     Overlay 70/90/99 percent contours for Stages A, B, C, and D on the
     same axes.  This shows what is lost or reshaped by transport and by
     detector visibility.

  B. Composition maps
     In each accepted bin, show the fraction of O0, O1, O2, O4, O5, etc.
     This directly answers "what makes up the visible Lambda topology?"

  C. Origin-to-visible flow plots
     Use a Sankey or migration matrix:
       primary species -> exit species -> visible topology category

  D. Acceptance maps
     Plot A_topo(x) in hadron-centric planes such as
       (p_Lambda, cos(theta_Lambda))
       (decay length, daughter opening angle)

  E. Lost-space maps
     Plot f_final(x) * [1 - A_topo(x)] to identify where final-state Lambda
     events are produced but not captured by the topology definition.

  F. Geometry maps
     x-z and y-z maps of true Lambda decay vertices, split by accepted and
     failed events, to expose geometric acceptance and fiducial effects.

  G. Companion-object panels
     For visible Lambda-topology events, show the rates of visible kaon,
     visible gamma / EM, and low-extra-activity categories.

  H. Stratified cutflows
     Waterfall or cutflow plots from Stage A to Stage D, split by origin
     class.  This is the most compact way to show where each component is
     lost.

Encoding rules for readable figures
-----------------------------------

Use one visual encoding channel per concept:

  * color       = origin class or detector category;
  * line style  = stage (A, B, C, D);
  * panel column = generator;
  * panel row    = beam mode or truth-visible working point.

Practical rules:

  * do not put more than one filled density on the same panel;
  * use contour-only overlays when multiple stages are shown together;
  * keep axes identical across generators;
  * annotate every panel with the same working point and beam weight;
  * keep one legend vocabulary for all figures.

Minimum figure set
------------------

A compact note can be built from the following figure families.

  F1. 1D normalized spectra
      E_nu, W, p_Lambda, decay length for Stages A/B/C/D.

  F2. Stage coverage contours
      (E_nu, W), (Q2, W), (p_Lambda, cos(theta_Lambda)),
      (decay length, opening angle).

  F3. Composition maps
      Visible Lambda-topology composition by origin class.

  F4. Acceptance maps
      A_topo for loose, nominal, tight working points.

  F5. Geometry maps
      Decay-vertex maps for accepted vs failed events.

  F6. Companion-object summaries
      Fractions of visible kaon, visible gamma / EM, low extra activity,
      CC-tagged muon, and no-visible-muon categories.

  F7. Origin-flow plot
      primary species -> exit species -> visible category.

  F8. Cutflow
      Stage A -> B -> C -> D, split by origin class and generator.

